At the moment, to facilitate adoption of a feature we implemented to improve manipulation of sprints throughout JIRA's UI, *the Sprint field will be added to all Create/View/Edit screens (the screens used by the project) each time a new project is created and enabled for Agile*. This is actually an improvement based on the highly voted ticket, as mentioned in [GHS-10767|https://jira.atlassian.com/browse/GHS-10767].

However, in the case where the screens are shared accross multiple projects, this automation (sprint will gets automatically re-added into screens) will affect other projects, as they share the same screens. It would be better to have the *options* for the Sprint field to *NOT be automatically re-added* whenever a new project is created and enabled for Agile.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Software Cloud*. Using *JIRA Software Server*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JSWSERVER-12016].
  {panel}

h3. Steps to reproduce

# Login to JIRA as an Administrator;
# Create an Epic in a project;
# Now create a new issues and choose a different project;
# Click on the dropdown of the "Epic Link" field;
# The Epic created before in a different project is listed in this project as well;

h3. What is needed

We want the "Epic Link" field to display only Epics from the selected project.

{{As an administrator I would like to quickly add a set of dates e.g. US Bank Holidays, to a board's non-working days}}



Original summary: Button to add US bank holidays to non-working days
Original description: As an administrator of LawGives, I would like a quick button to automatically add all US Bank Holidays to the non-working days.  (See screen shot)

h5. Steps to replicate:

- Create 3 Issues in a clean board: ISSUE-1, ISSUE-2 and ISSUE-3 keeping the same order in the Backlog;
- Perform a JQL search of the "ISSUE" project ordered by Rank - it will show ISSUE-1, ISSUE-2 and ISSUE-3;
- Now create a Sprint in this board and add the ISSUE-2 to this Sprint;
- Perform a JQL search of the "ISSUE" project ordered by Rank:

h5. Actual behavior:
The filter result will show ISSUE-1, ISSUE-2 and ISSUE-3;

h5. Expected behavior:
The filter result should bring ISSUE-2, ISSUE-1 and ISSUE-3;

The priority of an Issue in a Sprint should be higher than an Issue in the Backlog, since the users will work on the Sprint, and not in the backlog. However, if you search for those issues ordering by the Rank to use as a report, for example, it will show us an incorrect view of the Issues.
